<TEXT>
for the first time in 50 years the metropolitan 
opera has treated audiences to richard wagners mammoth ring 
cycle the oldfashioned way performing all four operas within a 
single week as the composer intended 
and what a treat it was 
seen in its 17hour entirety last week the production though 
not as adventurous as some would have liked bore out most of the 
hopes of those who have watched it gradually unveiled over the last 
2 years and it proved itself an instant crowdpleaser drawing 
lusty cheers from a standingroomonly crowd of nearly 4000 who 
paid up to 620 apiece for the four performances 
the staging by otto schenk with strikingly traditional sets and 
costumes by guenther schneidersiemssen brings to life with loving 
care wagners fantastical world of dwarfs dragons and demigods 
shunning the current habit of squeezing wagners untidy 
mythmaking into a political economic or psychological mold 
schenk schneidersiemssen and conductor james levine aim to let 
the drama and the music unfold on their own terms they may not 
have any new insights into this epic about the theft of a golden 
ring and the disasters that befall all who pursue it but they do a 
magnificent job of retelling the story as wagner wrote it 
the naturalistic sets and costumes depict the fairytale scenes 
and characters for what they are and nothing more the rhinemaidens 
are really mermaids not prostitutes as in one production and 
their river is not a hydroelectric dam wotan is really the king of 
the gods not a 19th century capitalist siegfried is really a 
noble young warrior not a garage mechanic 
ironically this literal interpretation has brought down the 
wrath of some critics who accuse the met of pandering to the 
reactionary tastes of wealthy patrons who financed the production 
but levine who is also the mets artistic director has 
defended the conservative choice on grounds that the company needs 
a solid production it can live with well into the next century not 
one that will seem dated or illconceived within a few years 
with no external viewpoint to hold the audiences interest the 
singing and orchestral playing must be special indeed if the 
production is to work its magic and here the met played its strong 
suit the orchestra sounded splendid all week and levine propelled 
the music forward with a fine sense of dramatic tension 
among the singers hildegard behrens once again showed that she 
is the finest bruennhilde of the postbirgit nilsson era though 
she lacks the overpowering vocal resources of a great wagnerian 
soprano she makes up for that with dramatic intensity as she 
changes before our eyes from a frisky young valkyrie to a 
passionate and then betrayed lover and finally to a compassionate 
woman whose sacrifice returns the ring to its rightful owners the 
rhinemaidens 
james morris was a superior wotan his brilliant high notes 
cutting through the heavy orchestration with ease another 
magnificent bass matti salminen carried off the rare feat of 
appearing in all four operas as fafner a giant in das 
rheingold transformed into a dragon in siegfried as 
hunding in die walkuere and as hagen in goetterdaemmerung 
other singers who made memorable contributions included franz 
mazura and graham clark as the brother dwarfs alberich and mime 
helga dernesch as wotans nagging wife fricka but as waltraute in 
goetterdaemmerung the high notes were too much for her 
siegfried jerusalem as the crafty god loge brigitta svenden as the 
prophetess erda and marianne haeggender unusually sweetsounding 
as the goddess freia 
as the romantic lovers siegmund and sieglinde robert schunk and 
ellen shade looked convincing and sang acceptably but were no vocal 
match for the team who appeared in earlier performances gary lakes 
and jessye norman 
a bigger problem was the siegfried of toni kraemer he acted 
with animation but had to press his voice in the upper register and 
often sounded harsh or flat the world is still waiting for a true 
heldentenor who can do justice to this killer role 
the met is offering one more complete ring cycle this week with 
gwyneth jones as bruennhilde william johns as siegfried and hans 
sotin as wotan it will be back three more times next spring and 
will be televised over four consecutive nights in june 1990 by the 
public broadcasting service 
